Certified Substitute Teachers
Half-day and full-day vacancies for certified substitute teachers. NYS teaching certification is required. Start date Sept. 20, 2021. Instructional application is available online and in the District Office. Application deadline August 24, 2020. Send letter of interest, resume, completed application, letters of recommendation, proof of NYS certification and copy of college transcripts to: Dr. Patricia Follette, Superintendent, Whitney Point Central School District, P.O. Box 249, Whitney Point, NY 13862. For more information, call (607) 692-8313.

post_text: The Officers of the New York State Public High School Athletic Association (NYSPHAA), voted to delay the official start date of the Fall 2020 sports season to September 21st, cancel the Fall 2020 Regional and State Championships and prepare to implement a condensed season schedule in January 2021 if high school sports remain prohibited throughout 2020 due to COVID-19. This decision comes at the recommendation of the NYSPHAA COIVD-19 Task Force. See details: http://nysphsaa.org/Portals/0/COVID%2019/COVID%20Task%20Force%20Meeting%20PR%20071620%20FINAL.pdf?fbclid=IwAR3ADezGkcIAcW5i6f0HhsKR0fscJBnY_TMKhdfGXri5GdixWJqopYmrsKc

post_text: Whitney Point Girl Scout Troop leaders Emily Jordan and Dana Wood and their troop continued to meet virtually during the pandemic and found inspiration for their bronze award project. The troop wrote and illustrated a book about overcoming challenges. The scouts noted, " we hope that when you read it you will realize that sometimes good things can come from challenges too." The troop donated a hard copy to CEA and TRA for their school libraries. See a video slideshow of their book, Without Rain There Would Be No Rainbows: https://spark.adobe.com/video/kqEX7iQObhIlE?fbclid=IwAR1ckYeLBA2q7jrp9-a2_VHUWl59LSQuzpLSH7ZWy-nG2nwBWNMzk7Au0aU

The 2020-2021 proposed district budget has passed, 562-323. The bus proposition and library proposition also passed. Board of Education candidates were elected as follows: Stephanie Champney, 672 votes - 1 year term; Kathy Driscoll, 692 votes - 3 year term; Eddie Maslin, 701 votes - 3 year term; Tom Tasber, 697 votes - 3 year term.

Thank you to our district voters for your continued support!

post_text:
Seniors Get Parking Lot Tribute:

Whitney Point CSD Transportation Department employees, Eagles Nest Booster Club members and several volunteers teamed up on Friday to create a unique tribute to the WPHS Class of 2020. Buses were positioned in the shape of the letters "W" and "P" and the first name of each senior student was written in colorful chalk on the parking lot asphalt. Booster Club President Russ Dunham used his drone to take aerial photos. Many thanks to all who helped make this happen!
text:
Seniors Get Parking Lot Tribute:

Whitney Point CSD Transportation Department employees, Eagles Nest Booster Club members and several volunteers teamed up on Friday to create a unique tribute to the WPHS Class of 2020. Buses were positioned in the shape of the letters "W" and "P" and the first name of each senior student was written in colorful chalk on the parking lot asphalt. Booster Club President Russ Dunham used his drone to take aerial photos. Many thanks to all who helped make this happen!

post_text:
SUNY BROOME SCHOLARSHIP DEADLINE EXTENDED

Attention Seniors:
Some of you may have already heard, but SUNY Broome has decided to extend the scholarship deadline for incoming students to Friday, June 12 to be sure that all incoming students have a chance to apply. Apply using the link below.

Each scholarship recipient will be notified via their SUNY Broome email that they have been selected. Students will need to log into the scholarship system and complete the follow-ups to accept the award and submit a thank you note to the donors. SUNY Broome will mail the scholarship certificates later in the summer to students' homes since they will not have the information in time for the awards ceremonies.

Apply for a SUNY Broome scholarship:

https://sunybroome.awardspring.com

Northern Broome is behind the rest of the County in Census responses. Currently, about 45% of Triangle, 47% of Lisle and 36% of Nanticoke residents have completed the Census. Our district needs to be represented!
Go to https://my2020census.gov/ or call 1-844-330-2020 to complete your Census today!
Did you know:
It only takes ten minutes to complete the Census, and it will impact the district for the next ten years.

The 2020 Census will inform hundreds of billions in funding for things like education and health programs that communities need? Let's get our share!

We encourage elementary students to watch the video story time with Interim NYS Education Commissioner Shannon Tahoe. Reading with children has many cognitive, social and emotional benefits. When children read or when they are read to they develop a stronger vocabulary and a range of knowledge and skills that lead to reading success. Reading also strengthens social emotional development by providing children with a greater range of words to describe their feelings and a stronger emotional toolkit.

Let's keep kids reading each day while they are at home! Click here for the video:

https://vimeo.com/412774202

United Way of Broome County is organizing a face mask distribution initiative through their 211 Information and Referral Center.

If you or someone you know needs a cloth, reusable mask, please dial 211.

United Way is working with the county to coordinate mask donations that get professionally cleaned, packaged and distributed, typically within a 1-2 day turnaround time. Most are picked up at United Way, but delivery can be arranged for those who are homebound or without transportation.

ATTENTION STUDENT ATHLETES: The NCAA Eligibility Center has received a number of inquiries regarding potential adjustments to the initial-eligibility certification process as a result of closures, cancellations and changes due to COVID-19. We are working closely with our member institutions and making progress toward national solutions to the issues raised for both Divisions I and II. We look forward to communicating the details of these adjustments in the coming weeks upon complete review through our governance processes.
For information on COVID-19, please visit ncaa.org/COVID-19 and continue to monitor for more information from the Eligibility Center at on.ncaa.com/EC_COVID.

post_text: With the recent closure of businesses across the state, many New Yorkers are at risk of losing their health insurance coverage as a result of COVID-19. Many are likely to be eligible for health coverage with financial assistance through NY State of Health due to their loss of coverage and income. NY State of Health opened a Special Enrollment Period last month for people who are uninsured, and the Marketplace has started an awareness campaign to let people know that NY State of Health is there as a safety net in difficult times like these. For more information, see the attached letter.
text: With the recent closure of businesses across the state, many New Yorkers are at risk of losing their health insurance coverage as a result of COVID-19. Many are likely to be eligible for health coverage with financial assistance through NY State of Health due to their loss of coverage and income. NY State of Health opened a Special Enrollment Period last month for people who are uninsured, and the Marketplace has started an awareness campaign to let people know that NY State of Health is there as a safety net in difficult times like these. For more information, see the attached letter.

post_text: After watching the Merry-Go-Round Playhouse performance of "Huff and Puff," students in Miss Lawrence's first grade class worked collaboratively to create Three Little Pigs houses. This was a STEAM challenge that tasked them with building a house from any classroom materials that would hold up to the Big Bad Wolf - a hairdryer! Students drew blueprints for their idea, built their structure, tested it with the hairdryer and talked about how they might change or improve their structure. Tree houses, block buildings and tents were created, and all the houses kept out the Big Bad Wolf!

post_text: A group from Whitney Point attended a Student-Athlete Leadership Conference entitled "Positive Leadership is Powerful Leadership" on May 4th at the Clark Sports Center in Cooperstown, NY. Students Alex Barnhart, Katelin Bailey, Madison McCall and Killian Prentice attended the event along with Coach Danielle Montesano and Director of Athletics Murphee Hayes. They attended a variety of workshop sessions, participated in physical activities, networked with others and discussed service learning projects.

post_text: CEA first-graders recently participated in a free nutrition education program through Cornell Cooperative Extension. Students were engaged in learning about food groups, recommended daily servings, health benefits of fruits and vegetables from all colors of the rainbow, sugar content of various beverages, and overall making healthy choices for themselves. Taste testings were offered for a yogurt and apple snack, fresh peppers, and water flavored with fresh fruit. Yum!

post_text: Fourth grade students completed math-related challenges as they ventured through Geometry Town in the TRA STEM Lab. Students were tasked with designing their own towns that included geometry-related components, and classes chose a region of New York state to represent with a collaborative construction activity. It was so impressive to see their creative use of math materials! Geometry Town was a culimnating activity after the fourth graders recently completed a geometry unit in math.
